 understand equality not as something grounded in shared characteristics but as something people enact when they refuse to be considered inferiors. At a time when the supposedly shared belief in human equality is so patently not shared, the book makes a powerful case for seeing equality as a commitment we make to ourselves and others, and a claim we make on others when they deny us our status as equals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEquality. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aA Theory of Justice.  aActivism.  aAffirmative action.  aAfrican Americans.  aAgainst Democracy.  aAnti-imperialism.  aBlack people.  aBribery.  aCapitalism.  aCitizenship.  aColonialism.  aConsideration.  aCopyright.  aCriticism.  aCritique.  aDemocracy.  aDetermination.  aDiscrimination.  aDivision of labour.  aEconomic inequality.  aEgalitarianism.  aEmancipation.  aEmbarrassment.  aEmployment.  aEqual opportunity.  aEquality before the law.  aEthnocentrism.  aExclusion.  aExplanation.  aFeminism (international relations).  aFeminism.  aFrancis Fukuyama.  aGender equality.  aGender neutrality.  aGender role.  aGender studies.  aHannah Arendt.  aIdentity politics.  aIllustration.  aIncome.  aIndigenous peoples.  aInjunction.  aInstitution.  aIntersectionality.  aJohn Rawls.  aJust society.  aLegislation.  aLiberalism.  aMeritocracy.  aMichael Walzer.  aMinority group.  aModernity.  aMulticulturalism.  aNancy Fraser.  aNew feminism.  aObedience (human behavior).  aOf Education.  aOppression.  aPatriarchy.  aPersonhood.  aPhilosopher.  aPhysiognomy.  aPolitical agenda.  aPolitical correctness.  aPolitical philosophy.  aPolitician.  aPolitics.  aPoverty.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPublic policy.  a